{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585764"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15012"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15012"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.13,0.2,0.13,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7700"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5264"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18815"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETetracyclines are broad-spectrum antibiotics that inhibit bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most effectively treated with tetracyclines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chlamydia trachomatis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus aureus","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Candida albicans"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETetracyclines are particularly effective against \u003Cstrong\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/strong\u003E and are considered first-line treatment for these infections. They work by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit, preventing attachment of aminoacyl transfer RNA and thus inhibiting bacterial protein synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less suitable for tetracycline therapy:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/strong\u003E has intrinsic resistance to tetracyclines through efflux pumps\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E commonly show acquired resistance to tetracyclines, making them poor choices for empiric therapy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/strong\u003E is a fungus and therefore intrinsically resistant to antibacterial agents like tetracyclines\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETetracyclines remain particularly useful for treating infections caused by intracellular organisms like \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma\u003C/em\u003E, and \u003Cem\u003ERickettsia\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tetracyclines are broad-spectrum antibiotics that inhibit bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit","Tetracyclines are first-line treatment for Chlamydia trachomatis infections","Tetracyclines are ineffective against fungi and have limited use against many common bacteria due to resistance"],"references":["Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","O\u0027Neill CE, Seth-Smith HMB, Van Der Pol B, Harris SR, Thomson NR, Cutcliffe LT, Clarke IN. Chlamydia trachomatis clinical isolates identified as tetracycline resistant do not exhibit resistance in vitro: whole-genome sequencing reveals a mutation in porB but no evidence for tetracycline resistance genes. Microbiology (Reading). 2013 Apr;159(Pt 4):748-756. doi: 10.1099/mic.0.065391-0. Epub 2013 Feb 1. PMID: 23378575.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15012"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52304"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T21:07:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T21:12:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7700"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66850"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"da